& [Inference] is bounded and restrained
  + [primary_observation] is alpha tuning cleanly parameterizes the Cesaro smoothing tradeoff
  + [positive_result] is every alpha above zero improves bridge residual over sharp in every bounded row
  + [negative_result] is every alpha above zero also increases exact cutoff residual against -zeta_prime/zeta on average, with alpha 1.0 the largest increase
  + [identity_boundary] is no tested alpha dominates both bridge residual and cutoff bias, so the branch has found a diagnostic Pareto coordinate rather than a fused explicit/Euler identity
  + [answered_question] is no bias-corrected superiority appears in this bounded pass; yes, the tradeoff is clear enough to pause kernel multiplication unless a new source-defined purpose appears
  + [next_reasonable_coordinate] is return to whole-field synthesis or define a new non-kernel bridge object; do not keep adding kernel variants only to refine the same Pareto curve

  = must: treat alpha tuning as finite Re(s)>1 bridge-surface diagnosis only
  = must: report cutoff bias whenever reporting alpha bridge improvement
  = must: preserve alpha 0 sharp as the lower-bias finite cutoff baseline
  = must: treat alpha 1 Cesaro as the bridge-residual endpoint, not as a universally best kernel
  = must: pause kernel multiplication unless a new source-defined purpose or whole-field object requires it
  - never: claim RH proof, disproof, independent zero certification, critical-line authority, universal bridge identity, or explicit/Euler fusion from this atlas

